cs.AI, cs.CL, cs.DB, cs.SI, cs.CY 

This paper involves the use of statistical learning methods and semantic heterogeneity in clinical data, which suggests it could belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) or Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) sub-categories. The creation of the Opioid Drug Knowledge Graph (ODKG) and its use to normalize drug strings in a clinical data warehouse suggests it could also belong to the Databases (cs.DB) sub-category. The use of the ODKG to generate summary statistics of opioid prescription trends across US regions suggests it could belong to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) or Cybersecurity (cs.CY) sub-categories.
